<TEXT>
cubanborn state sen ileana roslehtinen romped to 
the republican nomination tuesday in the race to succeed the late 
rep claude pepper while a cubanborn former city commissioner and 
a prominent jewish attorney headed to a democratic runoff 
attorney gerald richman claimed momentum as he narrowly led a 
sevencandidate field in the ethnically diverse district former 
miami city commissioner rosario kennedy also cubanborn had been 
the frontrunner but was criticized for late negative campaigning 
she ran just behind richman who in his stump speech said the 
us house slot was an american seat peppers niece jo ann 
pepper fell short of the aug 15 runoff for the district 18 seat 
it is really incredible said ms roslehtinen who was 
carrying nearly every precinct with 80 percentplus totals were 
quite humbled and really flabbergasted we really just hoped for a 
victory without a runoff 
elections officials said turnout was best in the little havana 
precincts the aug 29 special election to fill the seat pepper had 
held for the democrats since 1962 could result in election of the 
first cubanamerican in congress 
while the democrats battle in a runoff campaign ms 
roslehtinen will get help from a fundraising visit wednesday by 
vice president dan quayle for the state republican party and she 
will film a new television commercial thursday we are going to 
charge ahead she said we dont let up for one minute 
in unofficial returns from all 146 precincts ms roslehtinen 
36 had 16555 votes or 85 percent fellow cubanamerican carlos 
perez 57 had 1997 votes or 10 percent insurance broker david 
fleischer 54 had 555 votes 3 percent and evangelist john 
stembridge 51 had 456 votes or 2 percent 
in the heated democratic race richman 48 had 5513 votes or 
28 percent while ms kennedy 44 had 5402 votes or 27 percent 
ms pepper 39 had 4757 votes or 24 percent 
some 1000 democratic absentee ballots remained to be counted 
wednesday 
professor marvin dunn 48 had 1625 votes or 8 percent and 
real estate agent sonny wright 54 had 1476 votes or 7 percent 
they are both black 
businessman bernard anscher 67 had 662 votes 3 percent and 
striking eastern airlines pilot john paul rosser 38 had 264 
votes or 1 percent florida hasnt elected a black congressman 
since reconstruction 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
pepper a liberal champion of the elderly and poor drew no 
opposition in 1988 he died may 30 at age 88 and his death left 
the republicans with a 108 majority in the states congressional 
delegation 
the district includes the retirement communities of miami beach 
predominantly black neighborhoods such as liberty city heavily 
cuban neighborhoods and affluent coral gables 
the elections office said the districts 100198 registered 
democrats comprised 16028 hispanics 32183 blacks and 51987 
nonlatin whites the 71620 registered republicans comprised 
46738 hispanics 23656 nonlatin whites and 1226 blacks 
but the figures for hispanics are low because the office counts 
only those who were born in hispanic nations unofficial estimates 
that include secondgeneration hispanics run to about half of the 
registered voters 
ms lehtinen an educator and conservative married to us 
attorney dexter lehtinen led candidates in fundraising with more 
