<TEXT>
since east germany was founded 40 
years ago west germanys largest publishing chain has snubbed its 
socialist sibling by placing quotation marks around every reference 
to the state 
but starting today axel springer newspapers and magazines will 
end the practice that has irked authorities in east berlin 
springer officials said 
the quotation marks have cost the publishing empire journalistic 
accreditation in the neighboring socialist state and readership 
among much of west germanys leftleaning populace 
but far from conceding defeat in the ideological battle the 
publishers contend the war against the division of germany 
continues 
the hope for reunification is unshaken manfred schell 
editorinchief of the conservative daily die welt wrote today 
but in light of changes in eastwest relations the barriers to 
improving the flow of information between the political blocs must 
fall schell said 
the giant springer publishing network includes europes 
largestcirculation daily hamburgbased bild zeitung which sells 
nearly 5 million copies daily it also includes the influential 
berliner morgenpost and bonns die welt 
despite springers broad audience its journalists have been 
denied accreditation to work in east germany on the grounds that 
the companys editorial policies are insulting to the berlin 
government 
a spokesman for the east german foreign ministry said the 
government had no immediate comment on springers reversal 
schell hinted in his editorial that the newspaper considered the 
dropped quotation marks a step toward gaining permission to report 
from east germany referring to east germany as ddr the german 
abbreviation for deutsche demokratische republik was the protest 
of the publishing chains founder axel springer who died nearly 
four years ago 
germanys division after world war ii weighed heavily on 
springer who moved his prospering business from his native hamburg 
to west berlin in 1967 
after construction of the berlin wall in 1961 he put up a 
lighted readerboard to flash news from the west across the barrier 
springer also issued political and moral guidelines for the 
publications in 1967 and the first and foremost called for the 
reunification of germany 
from the 1949 founding of east germany springer publications 
refused to acknowledge the socialist government and the quotation 
marks demonstrated their disdain 
die welt administrative chief jens lueddeke said other west 
german publications also initially declined to acknowledge east 
german statehood using similar quote marks or skeptical references 
to the government 
but most dropped the practice after west germany recognized the 
east in 1970 
springer editors concede now that the quotation marks have now 
lost their meaning and in some cases simply confuse readers 
circulation of springers main dailies has fallen by as much as 
10 percent over the past few years and many attribute the drop to 
shifts within the west german populace toward detente with nations 
of the sovietled warsaw pact 
the number of people who can recall adult life in a unified 
germany is a minority die welt editor schell wrote 
with this step we come to grips with the developments in east 
and central europe in particular the reform efforts in hungary 
poland and the soviet union schell said 
