<TEXT>
a federal judge who was reprimanded for ruling 
on two general electric co cases while owning ge stock said he 
will institute safeguards to prevent it from happening again 
a judicial panel determined that us district judge thomas 
curran violated the us judicial code of ethics by ruling in the 
cases according to documents obtained tuesday by the associated 
press 
the code requires judges to disqualify themselves from any case 
in which they have a personal or financial interest 
in a letter william j bauer chief judge of the us 7th 
circuit court of appeals admonished curran to increase your 
diligence in searching out any future possible conflicts but said 
no other action would be taken 
because the violation unintended as it appears gives an 
appearance of impropriety to the actions we express our concern 
that they occurred said bauer who oversees the milwaukee 
district where curran presides 
curran could have faced suspension or a recommendation that he 
be impeached but bauer said those penalties would have been too 
harsh 
currans rulings in the cases where he had holdings were 
reported by the ap on may 30 that report triggered the 7th circuit 
review 
the judicial council is made up of the 11 active appeals judges 
in the 7th circuit and four district judges from the 7th circuit 
which covers indiana illinois and wisconsin 
upon being notified of the conflict curran publicly dismissed 
himself from the cases an action that allows interested parties to 
reopen the cases 
in a letter responding to the reprimand curran said he joined 
in the councils concern about the conflicts and instituted 
additional procedures and safeguards designed to prevent 
reoccurrence 
curran wrote he reviewed documents in both cases and i simply 
never connected up the defendant in each case with my investment 
the responsibility and blame must rest solely on my shoulders 
the ap discovered the conflicts by reviewing currans annual 
financial disclosure statements and crossreferencing his stock 
holdings with his case files 
the ap review showed curran has reported each year since 1985 
that he has held between 15000 and 50000 in ge stock he 
presided over unrelated cases involving ge medical systems in 1987 
and 1989 in both cases he ruled in favor of ge 
in the eastern district of wisconsin based in milwaukee lawyers 
are required to file a certificate identifying all interests in the 
case judges must then review that certificate and compare it 
against their financial records to make sure they do not have an 
interest 
in one of the two ge medical systems cases curran said a 
certificate of interest was not filed by either the defendant or 
plaintiff 
curran 64 was appointed to the bench in 1983 by former 
president reagan his 1988 disclosure statement showed net 
investments between 648030 and 1740000 generally in bluechip 
stocks his investments returned between 37147 and 112116 in 
1988 including between 1001 and 2500 in ge dividends 
</TEXT>
