hungary says it is risking social 
unrest rising unemployment and a possible backlash from the 
conservative right in its push toward a freemarket economy 
the government in a memo tuesday to a 24nation conference on 
aid to poland and hungary said it is determined to change its 
statecontrolled economy even if it initially causes social 
conflicts 
hungary warned however of widespread opposition if its 
campaign resulted in a sharp and sustained fall in the standard of 
living of the countrys 11 million people 
it urged more than 130 officials attending the meeting at the 
headquarters of the european community for financial aid hungarys 
foreign debt is about 18 billion the highest per capita in 
eastern europe 
the memo said the government was seeking as much as 3 billion 
in new western assistance from 1990 to 1992 
president bush and other key world leaders called for the 
meeting to draw up a western aid package that would encourage 
democratic change and economic reforms in poland and hungary 
they also urged emergency food shipments for poland 
at the oneday talks the united states pledged an additional 
50 million in food aid to poland beginning oct 1 to help ease 
the shortages caused by that governments moves toward a 
freemarket economy 
