drug czar william j bennetts national drug 
strategy calls for increased law enforcement but is short on 
specifics according to administration officials who have seen it 
while the program focuses on cocaine particularly crack it has 
virtually nothing on heroin dangerous prescription drugs that 
are diverted to illegal use or hallucinogens said one source 
theres only one sentence on all of that the source said 
tuesday 
the strategy report to the cabinet required by the 1988 
antidrug law that created the office of national drug control 
strategy strongly reflects public comments made by bennett since 
he took office five months ago 
the final report is due sept 5 
it reads like one of his speeches said one source 
another source said bennett wrote the strategy himself after 
gathering information from government agencies and drug experts 
all the sources spoke on condition of anonymity 
the strategy calls for an allout effort to eradicate domestic 
marijuana crops and to wipe out moneylaundering operations but it 
says nothing about domestic methamphetamine labs one source said 
however the source said there were few specific goals such as 
the number of drugtreatment beds the nation should have by 1991 
in the draft submitted monday 
the only goals included were that drugrelated admissions to 
emergency rooms and the drug use found by the national household 
survey on drug abuse should be reduced by 10 percent in two years 
and by 50 percent in 10 years according to one of the sources 
bennett warned last week that the strategy would contain some 
carrots and some sticks 
we will expect states to do certain things if they want 
federal funds he said then we will expect educational 
institutions to finally do certain things if they want education 
funds 
in the most recent draft those threats take the form of a 
possible loss of highway funds for states that fail to revoke 
drivers licenses from those convicted of drug offenses and a 
possible loss of federal education funds from schools that fail to 
have education department approved drugprevention programs and 
policies a source said 
threats in an earlier draft to revoke criminal justice funds 
were eliminated the source said 
senate judiciary chairman joseph r biden jr who spent eight 
years pushing for creation of the job said during bennetts 
confirmation hearing that he expected the strategy to include 
detailed goals 
one source said bennett planned to meet with senators in the 
next few days possibly to reduce expectations 
the strategy seen by the sources did not include matters such as 
international operations and interdiction efforts which are 
included in a separate classified document being reviewed by the 
national security council 
the nonclassified strategy under review by the domestic policy 
council reflects bennetts oftstated contention that the drug war 
must be aggressively fought on all fronts enforcement prevention 
and treatment 
no single strategy pursued alone or to the detriment of other 
possible and valuable initiatives can work to contain or reduce 
drug use the strategy says 
but what that means in terms of money was not immediately clear 
the draft strategy circulated monday included no budget figures 
bennett said in june that he expected to seek more money for 
drug treatment and probably more for prevention he said last week 
that the escalating cost of the drug war may eventually lead to the 
need for a tax increase 
the strategy stresses a need to rid inner cities of illegal 
drugs 
a paramount target of lawenforcement activity especially at 
the local level must be the disruption of those street markets for 
drugs in which retail demand and supply finally meet in a 
combustible mix 
it includes proposed antidrug legislation for states that 
closely resembles outlines bennett provided two weeks ago to a 
gathering of state legislators according to one source 
the policies bennett urged on the state legislators ranged from 
hiring more police judges and prosecutors and building more 
prisons to imposing civil fines of up to 10000 for those 
convicted of possessing small amounts of drugs 
