<TEXT>
president bushs cleanair bill could cost 
businesses and consumers money but it remains the best hope for 
breaking a decadelong stalemate a coalition of the nations major 
industries says 
there is no gift here for consumers workers or 
businesses coalition administrator william fay said tuesday in 
answer to environmental groups that contend the bush proposal is a 
sellout to industry 
representatives of the petroleum chemical and auto industries 
all members of the clean air working group offered a mixed review 
of the bush plan at a news conference 
fay said the legislation would dramatically control acid rain 
tighten auto and truck emission standards force some cities to 
adopt an alternative motor fuels program and cut ozone emissions 
and airborne toxic chemicals 
but some of the measures fay said would go too far in slashing 
industry profits hurting competitiveness and costing consumers 
money when pollution control costs are passed on 
the industry representatives criticized two cornerstones of the 
legislation use of alternative fuels for some motor vehicles sold 
in severely polluted cities and a cap on sulfurdioxide emissions 
that would prevent utilities from expanding when demand for 
electricity is rising 
sulfur dioxide is the main component of acid rain which has 
destroyed trees and lakes in the northeastern united states and 
canada 
despite the criticism fay said the bush plan should be the 
basic legislative text from which a final bill will be drawn 
it addresses serious issues such as ozone and toxic air 
pollution he said and the president has made a serious effort 
to consider costs and build flexibility into the bill 
the bill fay said is a much better alternative than competing 
bills backed by environmental groups those bills would give 
industry far fewer choices in devising ways to improve air quality 
fay and other industry representatives say bushs original 
annual cost estimate of 14 billion to 19 billion would be far too 
low and would cause layoffs because of expense to industry 
he wouldnt predict how many jobs would be lost or give 
industrys estimate of the cost 
the provisions that upset the industry group the most have been 
cited again and again by administration officials as cornerstones 
of the legislation 
the alternative fuels plan would require that in areas with 
severe ozone pollution at least nine cities vehicles with 
cleanburning fuel must be sold according to the following 
schedule 500000 in the 1995 model year 750000 in the 1996 model 
year and 1 million in each of the model years from 1997 through 
2004 
were suggesting the mandate should not be there because 
automakers arent certain the technology is perfected or that 
consumers would accept the cars fay said 
michael mason a lobbyist with the american petroleum institute 
said his oil industry trade group believes the proposal to be a 
big mistake saying there should be a level playing field in 
which all fuels should be able to compete 
mason said the environmental protection agency has mostoften 
mentioned methanol as the likely alternative fuel a product made 
from natural gas that likely would come from saudi arabia iran or 
the soviet union 
he contended the epa appeared to be biased against giving us 
petroleum companies the chance to produce a cleanerburning 
gasoline 
the bush plan also would reduce sulfurdioxide emissions by 10 
million tons by the end of 2000 based on 1980 levels but the 
measure also would cap emissions at the reduced level thus 
restricting growth of utilities unless they could further reduce 
their emissions from existing plants 
the cap on such emissions fay said is unnecessarily 
restrictive limits economic growth and makes it difficult to 
build new factories and power plants 
