<TEXT>
both the senate and house have bills to impose 
random drug testing on transportation workers but the measures 
still have most of the differences that kept them from being 
combined into a single law a year ago 
the senate commerce committee approved a bill tuesday that would 
require random and other testing of workers with safetyrelated 
jobs on planes trains trucks and buses while the house on monday 
passed a measure affecting only railroads 
similar bills passed both chambers last session but lawmakers 
failed to come up with a single law 
sen jack danforth rmo a sponsor of the senate version said 
the committees bill was the best way to prevent the lethal 
consequences of transportation substance abuse 
the commerce committee has jurisdiction over all modes of 
transportation while the house public works and transportation 
subcommittee that produced the house bill only covers railroads 
unlike the house approach danforth said the senate bill would 
give workers the incentive to seek rehabilitation before they are 
caught while the house measure would encourage workers to wait 
until they are caught 
both bills authorize employers to conduct drug tests before 
hiring on reasonable suspicion and after certain accidents as 
well as at random 
the senate legislation would require airline crews railroad 
crews and truck and bus drivers to submit to a variety of drug and 
alcohol tests 
rehabilitation programs would be set up by employers for workers 
who voluntarily seek help but the senate bill offers no guarantee 
of rehabilitation or continued employment for a worker caught by 
the tests or involved in a drugrelated accident 
the house bill would require testing only for railroad workers 
and would mandate employers to set up rehabilitation programs for 
workers caught under the influence of drugs or alcohol on the job 
the transportation department already has ordered a wide range 
of drug tests including random tests for railroad crews but they 
have been challenged in the courts the tests dont cover alcohol 
abuse 
if the senate measure is passed a conference committee would 
have to work out the differences in the two bills before a law 
could be sent to president bush for his signature 
</TEXT>
