<TEXT>
nissan motor co said today that it plans to make 
its car air conditioners and manufacturing processes free of 
chlorofluorocarbons the gases blamed for destroying the earths 
protective ozone layer by 1993 
nissan became the first of japans major automakers which are 
heavy users of chlorofluorocarbons cfcs to announce a total ban 
on the gases 
nissan spokesman shingo suzuki said the company helped by 
airconditioning makers such as hitachi ltd and calsonic corp is 
developing new car air conditioners that use a new substance to 
replace cfc12 
nissan has used some 1150 tons of cfc12 a year as coolants he 
said and a total of 1500 tons of cfcs a year for all purposes 
accounting for 12 percent of total cfc use in japan 
in the united states the spokesman said nissan already has 
stopped using cfc11 in the making of automobile bumpers and will 
do so in japan by the end of next year 
by the end of 1993 he said the company plans to replace 
cfc113 with water for cleansing automobile parts he said this 
will require the company to develop additional processes to dry 
parts after washing cfc113 dries instantly 
but it depends on the feasibility of cfc alternatives 
suzuki said if we can get stable supplies of new substitutes 
our goal is certainly attainable 
toyota motor co spokesman hiroshi hashimoto said although 
weve been considering environmental issues we havent reached the 
stage to announce anything concrete he said nissans move would 
prompt toyota to consider the issue more seriously and swiftly 
an official of the freon countermeasure division in the ministry 
of international trade and industry called such moves by the 
private sector very welcome 
companies that have to use additional machines and substances in 
the process of cutting cfc use can obtain tax reductions said the 
official speaking on condition of anonymity 
in montreal canada 38 countries agreed in 1987 to reduce 
production and use of the gases under the montreal protocol 
participating countries must freeze their cfc consumption this year 
at the 1986 level and reduce consumption to 5 percent of the 1986 
level by the end of 1999 
