the milwaukee journal on using aluminum baseball bats 
the same baseball fans who objected to lights in wrigley field 
domed stadiums and artificial turf are sure to get up in arms over 
reports that aluminum bats may be introduced into the big leagues 
aside from whatever value preserving tradition may hold keeping 
metal bats away from major league baseball makes common sense 
despite its many changes in recent years baseball remains 
pretty much the same game it has always been for that reason fans 
can reasonably argue whether wade boggs is a better hitter than 
rogers hornsby was and whether bob feller could make it in todays 
big leagues 
but aluminum bats would change the game much more drastically 
than even the designated hitter has changed it because they have a 
larger sweet spot than wooden bats aluminum bats can turn mediocre 
hitters into good ones and good ones into superior ones thus 
aluminum bats would change baseball in a fundamental way 
but they wouldnt improve it on the contrary giving hitters 
unprecedented new clout would upset the delicate balance between 
pitcher and batter that gives baseball some of its drama and makes 
it so much fun 
aluminum bats dont break and that makes them suitable for 
sandlot leagues which have to worry about money but they dont 
belong in the senior circuit 
