<DOCNO> AP890802-0102 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
women who try to reduce their risk of fractures 
and heart disease by taking estrogen supplements for many years 
after menopause may slightly increase their chances of breast 
cancer a study concludes 
some experts said doctors may have to consider the possibility 
of cancer when weighing the risks and benefits of putting women on 
estrogen after menopause however they caution that the evidence 
of a cancer link is still weak 
in my opinion the data are not conclusive enough to warrant 
any immediate change in the way we approach hormone replacement 
said dr elizabeth barrettconnor of the university of california 
san diego 
the study based on 23244 swedish women found that users had a 
10 percent overall increase in their risk of breast cancer after 
six years of taking the hormone 
however the risk varied depending on the kind of estrogen that 
women used those who took estradiol the most commonly used 
variety in sweden had nearly double the usual risk of breast 
cancer but the researchers found no increased risk among the 
relatively small numbers who used conjugated estrogens which are 
most frequently prescribed in the united states 
doctors often prescribe estrogen in combination with the hormone 
progestin in the belief that this will minimize any increase in the 
risk of uterine cancer which also is associated with estrogen use 
however the swedish study raised the possibility that this 
combination may actually heighten the risk of breast cancer 
women in the study who had used the combination for more than 
six years had four times the usual risk of breast cancer but the 
number of women studied was too small to be statistically 
meaningful 
this article raises concern about the new regimens noted 
dr lynn rosenberg of the sloan epidemiology unit at boston 
university combination therapy is becoming increasingly popular 
and recommended 
the study like other research found no danger from brief use 
of estrogen to relieve hot flashes and other symptoms during 
menopause 
the study was directed by dr leif bergkvist of university 
hospital in uppsala sweden and published in thursdays new 
england journal of medicine 
evidence of a link between estrogen and breast cancer is 
conflicting more than 20 studies have found no sign of an 
association but a few others suggest there may be a link 
estrogen is widely prescribed to older women to reduce their 
risk of heart disease and to stop osteoporosis which leads to 
broken bones some doctors recommended that women take the hormone 
for the rest of their lives 
this is an important public health question said dr 
charles hennekens of brigham and womens hospital in boston the 
breast cancer finding if confirmed would certainly be something 
that the physician would have to weigh in deciding whether to give 
estrogen 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

