<TEXT>
tropical storm dean developed into a hurricane with 
winds of 78 mph today as it surged westward toward the caribbean 
at noon edt the second hurricane of the atlantic season was 
centered near 175 degrees north latitude and 595 degrees west 
longitude or 425 miles east of san juan puerto rico rushing 
westward across the atlantic at 20 mph 
hurricane warnings were posted for the lesser antilles from 
guadeloupe to the us virgin islands said the national hurricane 
center in coral gables a hurricane watch was in effect for puerto 
rico dominica and martinique 
its very warm water theres not anything in the atmosphere 
to cause it to break up so basically it looks good for further 
development said meteorologist jesse moore right now its 
away from any land area but it could affect the easternmost 
islands of the lesser antilles within the next 6 to 12 hours 
rainfall of 510 inches and tides 3 to 5 feet above normal were 
possible 
south florida could be in danger in three or four days from 
dean which is called a cape verde storm because it formed off the 
west coast of africa 
when we see a hurricane like that we realize that it has the 
potential to move all the way across the atlantic and threaten the 
southeastern united states said hurricane center forecaster 
miles lawrence 
chantal the first hurricane of the season was downgraded to a 
tropical depression tuesday night after hitting texas near high 
island midway between galveston and port arthur it was blamed for 
at least two deaths 
dean began monday as the fifth tropical depression of the 
season it became a named storm monday night when its winds reached 
39 mph tropical storms become hurricanes when their top sustained 
winds hit 74 mph 
three other depressions have grown into named storms since the 
season began june 1 
</TEXT>
