<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh urged a 
senate panel wednesday to ratify an international antidrug 
trafficking treaty 
the pact will provide us with enhanced law enforcement tools 
and can lead to substantial advances in our international 
cooperative efforts to counter the illegal drug market 
thornburgh told the senate foreign relations committee 
the attorney general signed the un convention against illicit 
traffic in narcotic drugs and psychotropic substances on behalf of 
the united states last december in vienna 
the treaty includes a provision under which all the nations 
signing the convention have agreed to exchange evidence of criminal 
conduct and to extradite accused traffickers so that safe havens 
are no longer so readily available he said 
however thornburgh noted in response to questions from chairman 
claiborne pell dri that the treaty does not obligate countries 
to extradite their own nationals wanted on drugrelated charges in 
other countries 
the convention in and of itself is not going to provide a 
remedy to the extradition problem of colombia where the supreme 
court several years ago declared unconstitutional its extradition 
treaty with the united states that allowed drug traffickers to 
remain there when they were wanted on charges in the united states 
he said 
in addition thornburgh told sen joseph r biden jr ddel 
that the treaty would allow the united states to withhold 
investigative information from governments it perceives to be 
corrupt even if they have signed the document 
i think we would have no hesitation about doing that 
thornburgh said our obligation to our own citizens would 
transcend the treaty requirement to share information 
thornburgh said the president would decide whether the united 
states should seek extradition of someone overseas wanted on drug 
charges here when the state department doesnt want that to occur 
i have not had such a case arise thornburgh told biden 
the obvious instinct of a prosecutor is to prosecute 
however all of us recognize the prosecutions may have to be 
foregone for national security reasons 
mel levitsky assistant secretary of state for international 
narcotics matters attended the hearing but did not comment 
panamanian gen manuel antonio noriega was indicted by two 
federal grand juries on drugtrafficking charges in florida last 
year before thornburgh became attorney general the state 
department reportedly offered to drop the criminal charges against 
noriega if he would step down from power in panama 
the treaty calls for extradition of accused drug traffickers and 
the exchange of law enforcement information it also seeks to lift 
the veil of bank secrecy to help uncover moneylaundering 
operations requires supervision of the manufacturing and sale of 
chemicals used in the production of illegal drugs mandates that 
commercial carriers ensure their cargos are free of drugs and 
reaffirms the need for aggressive efforts in crop eradication and 
demand reduction thornburgh said 
the agreement requires each signatory to pass laws outlawing 
drug trafficking and money laudering while enabling the countries 
to seize drug profits but the laws of each country would take 
precedence 
thornburgh noted that all legislation by each country is 
subject to their constitutional principles and basic concepts of 
their legal systems 
the treaty thornburgh said will assist in the eradication of 
drugs and drugproducing laboratories and in preventing the 
transportation of precursor chemicals from this nation and others 
to the drugproducing countries for use in drug production 
the convention will also help to hinder the importation of 
drugs into the united states and prevent the transfer of the 
profits of the illegal drug trade back to the drug cartels he 
said 
</TEXT>
