<TEXT>
an experimental drug that stimulates rather 
than suppresses the immune system offers new hope in preventing 
rejection of transplanted human organs a researcher says 
the central dogma has been that if you stimulate the immune 
system thats bad dr randall morris director of the 
laboratory for transplantation immunology at stanford university 
said in a telephone interview were developing a new dogma that 
says its possible to use the immune system as an ally 
results of his research which includes successful testing in 
rodents were delivered wednesday to delegates to the triennial 
international congress on immunology in west berlin 
morris is testing lectins proteins derived from plant tissue 
he said lectins promote the growth of certain white blood cells 
called tsupressors while the action of the tsupressors is not 
clear they apparently restrain another type of white blood cell 
tkillers that attack foreign tissue including transplanted 
organs 
in experiments at stanford transplanted hearts in rats remained 
free of rejection for more than two years with no side effects the 
rats received 50 days of lectin treatment morris said in the 
telephone interview before his west berlin speech 
tests on humans are still years away he said 
morris said the lectins and two other experimental drugs will 
require extensive further testing but may someday reduce the need 
for large doses of cyclosporine a potent drug now used to prevent 
transplant rejection by depressing the immune system 
if our initial hopes are proven we are nearing a fundamental 
turning point in being able to keep transplant patients healthier 
and alive longer he said 
since human organ transplants began with kidneys about 35 years 
ago doctors have been unable to prevent the rejection of 
transplanted organs without compromising the immune system 
cyclosporine derived from a soil fungus helps prevent 
rejection by restraining the formation of white blood cells that 
attack transplanted organs but the daily oral doses can lead to 
kidney failure and high blood pressure 
two other transplant experts dr thomas starzl at the 
university of pittsburgh and dr robert corry chairman of surgery 
at the university of iowa and president of the united network for 
organ sharing said the use of lectins is virtually untested 
elsewhere 
starzl said morris idea of boosting the immune system to 
prevent organ rejection is a departure from current thinking on the 
problem 
morris said tests at stanford found lectins and two other drugs 
fk506 and rpm were effective in preventing rejection of 
transplanted hearts in rodents 
like cyclosporine he said fk506 and rpm are derived from 
fungus and work by depressing the immune system but they are more 
powerful 
fk506 developed several years ago by a japanese company was 
nearly 20 times more potent than cyclosporine in rodent testing 
morris said 
heart transplants in rats treated for two weeks with fk506 
survived eight times longer some longer than a year than 
recipients treated with cyclosporine even though the fk506 dose 
was only onefifth that of cyclosporine morris said 
starzl said his testing of fk506 indicated that while it may be 
powerful it was too early to predict its potential 
corry said the hope is that fk506 would be less toxic but more 
effective than cyclosporin 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

