<TEXT>
the cost of running the nations farms rose 
75 percent to 1184 billion in 1988 with farmers paying the bulk 
of their money for basics such as feed stock and machinery the 
agriculture department reported wednesday 
despite the increase the figure falls short of the record 
1318 billion farmers spent in 1981 just before the general 
financial crunch that stalled expansion in the agricultural sector 
in 1987 farmers spent 1101 billion for the buildings feed 
livestock rent labor seeds and plants fuels equipment and 
other components of raising livestock and crops 
average expenditures per farm last year were 54956 an 
increase of 4165 from 1987 
the increase outstripped the nations overall inflation rate 
which was 44 percent last year 
farms with annual sales of more than 100000 averaged 271481 
in expenditures and accounted for 68 percent of the total expenses 
they spent most of their money on services feed labor livestock 
and poultry farm machinery interest and fertilizer 
farms with sales of 40000 to 100000 had expenses averaging 
75371 and contributed 16 percent of the total their main 
expenses were services feed and machinery 
small farms those with sales under 40000 averaged expenses 
of 15464 and accounted for 15 percent of the total feed farm 
services and farm machinery were the leading expenses 
feed was the highest single cost item at 179 billion dollars 
in 1988 accounting for 151 percent of total costs the previous 
year feed cost 149 billion dollars and accounted for 135 
percent of expenses the highest single expense item that year as 
well 
the livestock and poultry that devour that feed cost 136 
billion accounting for 115 percent of the total last year the 
cattle swine and poultry including stud services cost 107 
billion accounting for 97 percent of the total 
the machinery to do the farm work cost 115 billion for 97 
percent of total expenses up from 109 billion 
a composite category farm services including rent was the 
largest one 246 billion accounting for 21 percent of the 
nations production expenses thats up from 24 billion in 1987 
that category includes cash and share rent vet supplies and 
services marketing and storage expenses insurance utilities 
leasing and transportation 
the only expenses to drop were interest payments which 
decreased 37 percent to 837 billion and building and fencing 
which dropped 103 percent to 223 billion 
the analysis dealt only with production expenditures and did not 
include figures for net income or profits 
annual spending by farmers reached its nadir this decade in 
1986 when many massively cut back their capital investments during 
a time of plummeting land values and rising debt burdens 
