<TEXT>
elementaryschool teachers are underreporting 
childabuse cases because they arent adequately trained to 
recognize or deal with them according to a study released 
wednesday 
fiftyseven percent of the more than 21 million reports of 
child abuse and neglect in 1986 involved schoolage children but 
only 163 percent of all reports filed with childprotective 
agencies originated with school personnel said the study by the 
national committee for prevention of child abuse 
the results of the survey point out a major problem in our 
efforts to prevent child abuse said committee executive director 
anne h cohn 
all states require teachers to report instances of child abuse 
ms cohn said 
but the committees survey found that only 50 percent of the 480 
elementaryschool teachers polled had received any training in the 
identification reporting and prevention of such cases she said 
most who said they received such training said it was inadequate 
the teachers surveyed taught first grade through sixth grade in 
39 school districts nationwide ms cohn said 
the chicagobased committee described as a national 
volunteerbased organization tried to assess teachers knowledge 
attitudes and beliefs about child abuse as well as their opinions 
on reporting child abuse and on prevention programs 
seventytwo percent of the teachers surveyed said they suspected 
that at least one of their students had been abused or neglected 
and 90 percent said they had reported such cases ms cohn said 
however reports commonly went to other school personnel such 
as a principal social worker or nurse only about 20 percent of 
the teachers said they reported abuse directly to childprotective 
agencies as required by most states laws 
only 57 percent of those polled said their districts had clearly 
defined polices on reporting suspicions of child abuse twentyfour 
percent didnt know if their districts had such policies although 
95 percent of the nations districts say they have clearly set 
guidelines for teachers to follow ms cohn said 
not only are many teachers unaware of the existence of those 
school policies but many do not seem to understand the policies 
that do exist she said 
according to the survey teachers are concerned about the legal 
ramifications of reporting child abuse even though most states 
grant immunity from lawsuits to teachers who report childabuse 
suspicions in good faith ms cohn said 
ms cohn said her organization believes administrators need to 
dramatically expand the education they provide their teachers so 
that teachers can feel much more comfortable and much more 
competent in their ability to identify and report child abuse 
the survey also asked teachers about corporal punishment and 
found that 57 percent felt it should be eliminated 
robert fathman chairman of the national coalition to abolish 
corporal punishment in schools said the drive to stop corporal 
punishment received a big boost this year with eight states 
banning the practice 
for the first time in the history of our countrys education 
system more than half of the school children in the us now 
attend schools that have prohibited hitting slapping punching 
hairpulling paddling or other firms of corporal punishment by 
educators fathman said 
