<TEXT>
officials who leak information to news 
reporters about federal criminal investigations may be prosecuted 
for theft of government property under a new policy announced 
wednesday by the justice department 
the department has decided to narrow a 11yearold policy 
against prosecuting officials who leak information to inform the 
public john c keeney a deputy assistant attorney general in the 
criminal division said in written testimony submitted to a 
congressional hearing 
in some circumstances reporters may be called to testify at 
grand juries to identify leakers although a subpoena would not be 
issued without the approval of the attorney general keeney said 
this aspect of the new policy which was unveiled at a joint 
hearing of two house judiciary subcommittees means the change 
could have little practical effect on leak investigations 
attorneys general historically have been unwilling to subpoena 
reporters who are usually the only source of evidence about who 
leaked them information 
but the new policy drew expressions of concern from civil 
libertarians who said it could be used to undermine a reporters 
first amendment protection against revealing confidential sources 
of information 
once the government is able to say we need this information 
because its material to a criminal investigation that raises the 
question of whether or not the protection of a confidential source 
is diluted said allan adler a washington media lawyer and 
former legislative counsel to the american civil liberties union 
i think it would be a definite misuse of the statute the 
statute was not designed with that in mind at all said rep don 
edwards dcalif chairman of one of the subcommittees it would 
be a very dangerous practice 
the policy in force since 1978 stated that it is inappropriate 
to bring a prosecution under the theft of government property law 
if information is leaked to inform the public and wasnt obtained 
by illegal means such as wiretaps or trespassing keeney said in 
testimony prepared for the committee 
the guideline contained in the united states attorneys manual 
was designed to protect whistleblowers and also to protect 
members of the media from prosecution for receipt of stolen 
property 
we have examined this policy and concluded it is too broad 
keeney said accordingly it is no longer applicable to government 
employees who leak information obtained from a criminal 
investigation 
moreover we will now consider prosecution of government 
employees under section 641 the theft statute in leak cases not 
arising out of criminal investigations if the employees conduct 
also violated some other provision such as the privacy act 
keeney said in his prepared statement 
such a leak could come from an fbi background investigation of 
someone under consideration for a cabinet position such as former 
sen john tower rtexas whose nomination to be defense secretary 
was killed amidst allegations of womanizing and drinking 
leaks of information from the fbi background investigation of 
tower drew criticism from congress and expressions of consternation 
by the bush administration 
keeney said the department is in the process of deciding 
whether the policy should be changed in other respects 
leslie harris legislative counsel at the aclu called keeneys 
announcement rather disturbing 
keeneys testimony was delivered at a hearing convened in the 
wake of congressional concern about leaks revealing a justice 
department investigation into financial irregularities in the 
office of rep william h gray iii dpa 
the investigation was disclosed during grays ultimately 
successful campaign to become house majority whip news reports of 
the gray case prompted attorney general dick thornburgh to order a 
leak investigation 
</TEXT>
