<TEXT>
a leading chinese intellectual believed to be 
a key link between deposed communist party chief zhao ziyang and 
the crushed student movement has escaped to the west an activist 
said wednesday 
chen yizi fled china to france several weeks ago on an 
underground railroad the hong kong activist said chen about 
50 was director of the institute of restructuring the economy an 
influential think tank when zhao was in power 
while in paris chen participated in meetings to form an 
overseas organization to push for democracy in china said the 
activist who spoke on condition of anonymity 
chen did not meet journalists nor were reporters informed of 
his presence in paris indeed some western reports said he had 
been arrested in beijing 
the hong kong activist who insisted on anonymity said chen 
remained in the west but declined to reveal his whereabouts there 
was no way to confirm the report by the activist but he has been 
reliable in the past 
several weeks ago an official at chens institute said he was 
resting 
so far the activist said about 30 people have fled china via 
the railroad among them have been essayist yan jiaqi and 
student leader wuer kaixi both of whom were in paris with chen 
they since have gone to the united states others such as marxist 
scholar su shaozhi fled china by other means 
a western diplomat in hong kong has said beijing authorities 
apparently wanted to use chen to prove that zhao had direct ties to 
the student movement his escape would complicate those efforts 
the activist said 
chen apparently met with student leaders during their twomonth 
movement for sweeping political change in china 
in a speech july 6 beijing mayor chen xitong criticized chen by 
name for presiding at a may 19 meeting during which pariticipants 
urged publicizing the inside story of the decisionmaking of the 
top leadership 
on may 20 martial law was declared in beijing the movement was 
crushed on june 3 and 4 when thousands of chinese soldiers entered 
the capital and killed hundreds perhaps thousands of unarmed city 
residents and students 
the western diplomat said chinese authorities wanted to prove 
chen conducted the meetings at the behest of bao tong zhaos 
former righthand man 
bao a member of the central committee of the communist party 
and director of the research center for reform of the political 
structure another prozhao thinktank was placed under house 
arrest shortly after the crackdown 
if the link between bao and chen could be established communist 
authorities would be able to implicate zhao directly in the student 
movement the western diplomat said 
so far the charges against zhao have been relatively vague 
the former chief of the communist party zhao was officially 
purged after the june 4 crackdown and accused of supporting the 
movement and counterrevolutionary turmoil more recently the 
staterun media have accused him being responsible for high prices 
and widespread corruption 
zhaos real involvement in the student movement is unclear 
his sympathy for the movement was obvious when he went to 
tiananmen square in midmay and with tears in his eyes told the 
students that he had come to see them too late 
the movement was supported by many intellectuals like chen yizhi 
and yan jiaqi who worked in thinktanks tied to zhao but it is 
unknown whether they were functioning under zhaos orders or acting 
on their own 
the hong kong activist said he looked on chens escape as a 
major victory against the current crackdown on the movement 
thousands of students and other participants in the campaign for 
freedom have been arrested since the repression began in early june 
the official media which started out reporting every major new 
arrest with headlines have stopped highlighting such activity the 
apparent arrest of student leader wang dan received no mention in 
the chinese press 
