<TEXT>
the senate passed a disaster assistance bill 
wednesday to send 885 million in relief to farmers hit by drought 
and severe weather 
the bill would make farmers eligible for federal aid if they 
have crop losses this year because of drought flooding freezing 
hail high winds or similar severe weather the measure also 
provides for payments to livestock producers facing droughtrelated 
feed and water shortages for their herds 
but the pricetag on the bill passed by voice vote in the senate 
is about 463 million less than the agriculture department has 
estimated would be the cost of a packaged approved by the house 
the senate bill provides for different eligibility standards for 
various crops but in all cases producers would receive payments 
designed to cover 65 percent of their lost income from crop losses 
in most cases the projected income levels will be based on 
federal crop subsidies or average market prices farmers would have 
received had they not suffered losses 
the most important thing about this bill is that all farmers 
are being treated fairly said sen patrick leahy dvt 
chairman of the agriculture committee those who suffer a 
significant loss will receive the same payment rate 65 percent of 
the applicable target price or loan rate 
we will not discriminate against any farmer who needs help 
leahy said this legislation treats farmers fairly whether they 
grow wheat corn hay or soybeans 
wheat and other crops have been damaged by the lingering drought 
across much of the great plains and flooding has destroyed rice and 
cotton in the south 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said winter wheat 
producers and other growers will be eligible for highpriority 
attention under provisions of the legislation 
this is not the best bill nor is it the kind of relief winter 
wheat producers and other program crops deserve he said but 
it is far better than the budgetbusting house bill which promised 
federal relief to every crop in america 
the house disaster relief bill required a minimum loss of 35 
percent for any crop to receive assistance with payments covering 
65 percent of lost income but unlike the senate bill the house 
measure called for 90 percent payments on crop losses of more than 
75 percent 
the senate dropped the higher payment level as a way of cutting 
the overall cost of the assistance package 
the senate also passed by voice vote rural development 
legislation designed to promote business investment and expansion 
in small towns it also is aimed at improving schools and health 
care for residents 
proponents had said federal assistance was needed because the 61 
million people living in rural areas face higher unemployment more 
hospital closings and higher poverty levels than their urban 
counterparts the rural economy also is more volatile because of 
its dependence on natural resources supporters contended 
the centerpiece of the package called the rural partnership 
act is a revolving loan fund program to provide 300 million in 
seed money over five years for new and expanding businesses 
the federal money which must be matched by money from local 
sources would go for loans and loan guarantees to create new jobs 
the revolving loan funds would be operated by states local 
governor or economic development groupst to ensure local control of 
the lending according to supportrs 
