<TEXT>
arguing with a big neighbor can be 
costly as nepal is discovering four months after losing the first 
round of a trade dispute with india 
already one of the worlds poorest countries landlocked and 
mountainous nepal faces difficult times unless it can come to terms 
with india on transporting its exports and imports across india at 
previously favored rates 
as a result of the dispute nepals deficit budget proposed for 
the fiscal year that started july 1 calls for expenditures to rise 
by 32 percent compared to 8 percent the previous fiscal year 
gasoline prices have been raised by 48 percent that reflects a 
threefold vulnerability of the nepalese economy steeper transit 
costs across india the declining value of the nepalese rupee and 
fluctuating crude oil prices in the middle east 
nepalese optimists say the trade and transit crisis with india 
will force nepal to develop its own infrastructure and become less 
reliant on others largesse 
pessimists say any such period of adjustment will take several 
years and further sap the resources of the country 
although the nepaleseindian dispute was sparked by treaty terms 
on bilateral trade and nepals access to indian transit facilities 
for thirdcountry trade many observers in the region see a deeper 
and to some a more sinister reason they describe it as indias 
growing power and ambitions as a major military political and 
economic force in the region 
india rejects such contentions 
nepals strength is in its majestic mountains and mystique that 
attract the tourists who provide about 20 percent of the countrys 
foreign exchange earnings another 20 percent comes from the export 
of carpets a business dominated by tibetan refugees who fled 
chinese rule in their homeland across the border 
its chief weakness is poverty nepals per capita annual income 
is 150 the world bank and united nations childrens fund record 
only two other countries with equal or worse economic misery 
bhutan where the per capita income also is 150 and ethiopia 
where it is 120 
nepal cannot remain an island of poverty any longer between 
the two countries in the region that are growing india and 
china foreign minister shailendra kumar upadhyaya said in an 
interview nepal also has to grow 
growth he added includes expanding ties beyond india 
india with a population of 880 million and nepal with 17 
million people had a special relationship between 1950 when 
the mountain kingdom emerged from hermitlike isolation and last 
march 23 when their trade and transit treaties lapsed 
nepal seeking to lessen dependence on its big neighbor has 
been steadily diversifying its trading partners over the past 15 
years but to import goods it relied on preferential rights to use 
indias seaports railroads and highways 
this year nepal wanted to renew the two separate trade and 
transit treaties but india insisted on a single treaty linking the 
two issues saying it was unfair for nepal to expect generous 
transit privileges to import goods from other nations which often 
as foreign minister upadhyaya and other nepalese officials 
acknowledged end up getting smuggled back to india and sold at a 
profit 
in 1975 82 percent of nepals foreign trade was with india by 
april 1989 it had shrunk to 28 percent according the fiscal 
198889 economic survey issued in july by king birendras 
government 
the proposed 198990 budget released at the same time calls 
for expenditures of about 736 million with a deficit of 818 
million to be financed primarily by foreign and domestic borrowing 
one of the biggest increases is in petroleum products which 
nepal has started purchasing on the international market instead of 
buying from india itself a net importer of oil 
petroleum and other nepalese imports still pass through india 
but india closed 13 of the 15 authorized border transit points when 
the march treaties lapsed and hassles at the two remaining points 
still crop up periodically 
for the nepalese consumer this has resulted in rationing and 
skyrocketing prices although the gasoline shortage of last spring 
and early summer is starting to ease most nepalese dont have 
cars but those who do are now paying the equivalen of 318 a 
gallon instead of 218 a gallon 
</TEXT>
