the federal reserves easing of its credit 
policy and the accompanying drop in interest rates have posed a 
325 billion question for investors in money market mutual funds 
should they sit tight with their money in the face of declining 
yields or look elsewhere for better returns 
if the past record is any guide the vast majority of money fund 
assets will stay put 
from 1975 when the earliest money funds had attracted less than 
4 billion to this year when their assets have swollen by more 
than 50 billion from 272 billion at the end of 1988 the 
longterm industry trend has shown almost uninterrupted growth 
periods of low or falling interest rates halted the funds 
expansion only briefly 
in 1983 for example when interest rates were falling and 
stocks were soaring in the early stages of a spectacular bull 
market money fund assets shrank by about 20 percent a year later 
they rebounded once again to new highs 
todays savers and investors have a wider range of competitive 
alternatives to choose among than ever before 
and thanks to rallies in the stock and bond markets funds that 
invest in those longterm securities have been producing 
substantially higher returns than money funds have offered 
late last month donoghues moneyletter a newsletter that 
tracks developments affecting fund investors issued a buy 
signal recommending a move from money funds to growth stock funds 
for venturesome investors 
but with all that many investors especially those who view 
their money fund holdings as a kind of modernday savings account 
may find few other choices that appeal more to them on the basis of 
both risk and potential reward 
the risks of stock market investing of course are well 
advertised at a recent yield of 885 percent analysts point out 
money funds still offer rewards close to the historical average 
annual return of 9 percent to 10 percent posted by the stock market 
what about the other alternatives taxfree money funds 
investing in state and local government securities whose interest 
is not subject to federal taxation recently were yielding about 
56 percent to 57 percent 
that put them at an unattractive level by donoghues reckoning 
even for an investor in the 33 percent bracket 
bank moneymarket deposit accounts have the allure of federal 
deposit insurance but their typical yields of about 65 percent 
languish far below their money fund competitors 
people wanting to lock in yields as protection against further 
declines in interest rates traditionally turn to longterm bond 
investments these days however they arent very well compensated 
for making that commitment 
in late july the yield available on the longestterm treasury 
bonds slipped below 8 percent 
