<TEXT>
it takes a mighty aggregation of man machine 
and fossil fuel power to move the gross national product a 
fraction of a point but in washington it can be done by 
researchers using only calculator power 
they do it again and again month after month revising 
important economic measurements some of which might have been 
when first announced the basis for decisions regarding business 
and economic policy 
revisions are a regular occurrence in statistics produced 
mainly by access to additional information or changes in 
methodology in some instances they are expected in some they are 
not in either event they can dismay 
several years ago for example rising retail sales were 
reported month after month giving the impression of a boom but 
when viewed after a year sales had risen only moderately 
the reason the monthly increases were based not on original 
figures but on later revisions repeatedly those revisions were 
downward meaning increases for the following months were from a 
base lower than originally stated 
some important revisions recently were made in estimates of 
gross national product perhaps the broadest of all economic 
measurements and one that often guides the direction of fiscal and 
monetary policy 
this revision raised the growth of real gnp for 1987 to 37 
percent from 34 percent a difference of 67 billion and for 
1988 to 44 percent from 39 percent a difference of 283 billion 
those arent puny numbers even in an economy where the value of 
a billion shrinks by the day in fact they are momentous figures 
when you consider that overheating vs recession was one of the 
biggest economic concerns in each of those years and that the gnp 
measurement was one of the primary indicators 
whatever decisions must be made in a critical time frame too 
immediate to wait for revisions 
battles are fought with the weapons on hand not with arsenals 
promised gen dwight eisenhower launched an invasion of europe 
after reading weather reports later found to be faulty later 
president eisenhower steered economic policy although in review 
the economic data he relied upon was less than perfect 
statistical faults are accepted the attitude seeming to be that 
nothing better is available if poor decisions are made so be it 
if good news comes in the revision enjoy it and hope it wont be 
revised out later 
good news did indeed come in the july revisions for one thing 
they made the trade deficit appear less ominous in one swipe 
erasing more than 25 billion from the negative 1988 numbers 
in 1988 it is now believed that the deficit stated in 1982 
dollars was 749 billion not 1002 billion the main reason for 
