<TEXT>
fifteen years after richard m nixon resigned 
as president to avoid the disgrace of removal from office 
historians and political observers say the republic paid a price 
but ultimately benefited from the ordeal 
and they say the impact of nixons crisis has been felt by 
every president who followed him chief executives since nixon have 
been more cautious candid and constrained 
washington lawyer philip w buchen who served as an adviser to 
nixons successor gerald r ford says that in retrospect nixons 
resignation was wholesome 
political scientist colin campbell author of managing the 
presidency says the experience left nixons successors pretty 
skittish for a while he thinks jimmy carter for one 
overreacted and was too weak 
historian richard s kirkendall of the university of washington 
says that while the event damaged the presidency it would have 
left us with more serious problems if nixon had been able to get 
away with it 
political scientist jim reichley of the brookings institution 
says the founding fathers pretty clearly expected that the 
impeachment process would be used more often than it has he says 
congress has been intruding on executive functions since it 
found the strength in 1974 to move toward the removal of a 
president 
a dissent comes however from bob hartmann who served as white 
house counselor to ford he says the nearimpeachment of nixon was 
unforunate there are other political remedies which are more 
routine and which can make presidents toe the mark and put the fear 
of god in them if theyre overreaching hartmann contends 
congress for instance can deny funds for presidential 
projects congress can so fix his clock that he cant do 
anything hartmann says 
buchen however says nixons continued tenure in office was 
having an adverse effect on the morale of the country and its 
status around the world it could have led to a threatening 
international incident we did not have a president who was 
actively governing nixon he says was concerned solely with his 
own survival that summer 15 years ago 
on the night of aug 8 1974 a few days after the house 
judiciary committee had recommended impeachment nixon went on 
television to announce that he would resign becoming the first and 
only president to have done so he said he no longer had a strong 
enough political base in congress to carry out the duties of 
office 
three days earlier he had surrendered the smoking gun 
watergate tape it revealed that within a week of the breakin at 
democratic party headquarters at the watergate in 1972 he had 
ordered an end to the fbis investigation whatever remaining 
support nixon had in congress collapsed 
the morning after nixons speech he resigned in a letter to the 
secretary of state and vice president ford took the oath our 
constitution works the new president said our great republic 
is a government of laws and not of men 
with the passage of time a sampling of historians and political 
observers shows agreement with fords assessment and these two 
points 
under the circumstances nixons resignation was healthy for 
the country 
the impact on nixons successors has been to curtail 
presidential adventurism to check the strongpresident 
weakcongress trend that started with franklin d roosevelt and to 
promote presidential candor and accountability 
i think the initial effect was to make presidents much more 
sensitive to the concerns of the public said buchen the exford 
adviser that was true of ford and carter it began to slip at 
the end of the reagan administration or we wouldnt have had the 
irancontra affair 
but even in the irancontra affair noted thomas e mann 
director of governmental studies at the brookings institution the 
record shows that reagans people used the word impeachment 
when discussing the possible consequences of oliver norths secret 
contrafunding activities 
it is important that they were sensitive to the possibility of 
impeachment mann said adding the legacy of nixon assures us 
that some warning signals are present for successive presidents 
even a strong president like reagan found himself 
substantially constrained by an active congres and a whole new set 
of statutes restricting presidential power he said 
watergate resulted in laws in these areas freedom of 
information limits on presidential warmaking powers and a 
presidents ability to impound funds appropriated by congress and 
limits on campaign contributions 
campbell a georgetown university political scientist said he 
finds it almost alarming that it came to the point that we almost 
had to do the same thing with ronald reagan 
he said the presidents age his popularity and his nearness to 
finishing his term saved reagan from an impeachment attempt but he 
finds reagans escape worrisome very seriously damaging to the 
fiber of the republic 
austin ranney chairman of the political science department at 
the university of california at berkeley said the difference 
between watergate and irancontra is that nixon knew what was 
happening while reagan always denied that he knew what was going 
on 
as for whether the nixon experience was good for the country 
ranney said it is never good to have a lawbreaking president but 
it was a wonderful thing that our system of justice and separation 
of powers worked to remove a president without an assassination or 
violence of any kind 
with the exception of hartmann who said we will never know 
the experts interviewed agreed nixon could not have avoided 
removal from office had he not resigned 
at the time he quit every member of the house judiciary 
committee had announced support for his impeachment by the house 
and even such staunch supporters as sen barry goldwater rariz 
had warned nixon he could not win in a trial by the senate 
people had had it with nixon and were finally ready to listen 
to the evidence said campbell 
theres no question he would have been impeached by the house 
and the senate would have convicted him said ranney 
kirkendall said president bushs conduct in office shows that 
bush has learned watergates lesson he noted bush consults 
conspicuously with congressional leaders and allies before making 
major moves he makes a big thing of it he said 
ranney said bush and others have learned that you cant get 
away with anything sooner or later truth will out and the truth 
shows that if you violated the law you will take the 
consequences 
</TEXT>
