<TEXT>
every morning traffic moves at a crawl along 
route 128 the high technology highway ringing boston some 
insiders say the pace of business inside the sleek corporate 
headquarters along 128 isnt any faster 
tactical decisions that take six weeks in boston can take 
anywhere from six days to six nanoseconds in california said 
sterling hager founder of a public relations firm that represents 
computer firms on both coasts 
after a year of falling profits and employment many companies 
along route 128 are going through a period of painful retrenchment 
and selfexamination and a common conclusion is that they need to 
become more agile less hierarchical and more willing to take risks 
in the last week three of the four largest computer makers in 
massachusetts wang laboratories inc data general corp and 
prime computer inc announced quarterly losses 
primes troubles have made it a takeover target and two other 
massachusetts hightech companies cullinet software inc and 
apollo computer inc already have been sold this year another 
former high flyer leading edge products inc is in bankruptcy 
all told high technology manufacturing companies in 
massachusetts have eliminated 7300 jobs in the past year and 
36100 since their peak in december 1984 the state department of 
employment and training says 
underlying route 128s woes are the maturing of the computer 
industry the slowdown in the national economy and the stiff 
competition that minicomputer makers face from workstations and 
ever more powerful personal computers 
but those trends do not entirely explain why some massachusetts 
computer firms are still prospering or why route 128s west coast 
counterpart californias silicon valley is generally healthy 
the substance of route 128s problem critics charge is style 
bostonarea executives in their buttondown shirts and brown shoes 
are more cautious and slowmoving than their california rivals in 
polo shirts and reeboks 
in northern california companies the hierarchy seems 
compressed said hager an account executive in sunnyvale might 
be reporting directly to the president the ceo or the founder in 
cambridge that person will speak to the communications manager 
who works for the vp of younameit who reports to the executive 
vp who whispers to the main force 
in part hager said the different management styles reflect 
cultural or lifestyle differences in part they are a matter of 
age 
the hightech superstructure on the west coast is run and 
managed by people in their 30s and the people who run the 
hightech companies on the east coast are mainly in their 50s and 
60s he said people in their 20s and 30s have no fear of 
anything 
stephen l josselyn a computer market analyst with 
international data corp in framingham agrees that decisionmaking 
is slower and product cycles longer along route 128 its just 
harder to get people to move on the east coast he said 
examples abound 
wang which pioneered the market for word processors lost 
ground when it failed to move quickly into personal computers it 
is now making a big push into document imaging products but it 
announced a 375 million quarterly loss monday some analysts say 
the familycontrolled company may have to find a substantial 
outside investor 
digital equipment corp the states largest computer maker 
also stuck with proprietary operating systems and failed to 
capitalize on the pc explosion now it is moving into open or 
nonproprietary software but digitals earnings have slipped this 
year and it has frozen salaries 
data general also is moving away from proprietary systems 
toward open software and reduced instruction set computing or 
risc technology which simplifies the circuitry of a computer 
and allows cost savings in a twoyear restructuring it has cut 
its work force from 16000 to 14000 and posted a 231 million 
loss for the quarter ended june 24 
data general spokesman michael f klatman calls the critics 
charges baloney 
from the time management made the decision to commit to open 
systems it took us just nine months to get our first products out 
the door he said thats something you never would have seen 
in this industry 10 years ago 
klatman and others point out that aside from sales of pcs and 
workstations the entire us computer market is slow 
minicomputer makers have been hit particularly hard squeezed 
between minisupercomputers on the high end and technical 
workstations on the low end said douglas j crook an analyst with 
dataquest inc in san jose calif 
it just so happens its an accident of nature that there are 
more minicomputer makers based in massachusetts and the 
traditional minicomputer is not growing at the rate of other 
areas said klatman 
