<TEXT>
the jury that convicted five former officials of 
princetonnewport partners lp and a former drexel burnham lambert 
inc trader of racketeering charges now must decide how much money 
they will have to forfeit to the government 
the jurors began deliberations on the forfeiture issue tuesday 
after hearing arguments from both sides 
assistant us attorney mark hansen said the defendants should 
relinquish salaries and other claims that could total more than 21 
million 
defense attorneys who have said they will appeal the 
conviction argued that the forfeiture sought by the government was 
excessive and violated the constitutional ban on cruel and unusual 
punishment 
on monday the manhattan federal court jury convicted the 
defendants of racketeering racketeering conspiracy conspiracy and 
numerous counts of mail and wire fraud 
the case marked the first time securities professionals were 
accused of racketeering under a controversial federal law aimed at 
combating mobsters and drug pushers the racketeer influenced and 
corrupt organizations law provides for heavy fines and lengthy 
prison terms in addition to forfeiture 
the trial received widespread attention because it grew 
indirectly out of the ivan boesky insider trading scandal that 
rocked wall street three years ago 
the largest forfeiture was sought from former princetonnewport 
partner james sutton regan his partnership interest was placed at 
133 million and his salary at 175 million 
from former drexel trader bruce lee newberg the government 
sought 25 million in salary 
the prosecution asked the jury to require forfeiture for the 
other princetonnewport defendants as follows former partner 
charles m zarzecki 11 million partnership interest and 267483 
in salary former partner jack z rabinowitz 791191 partnership 
interest and 454507 in salary former partner paul a berkman 
762613 partnership interest and 558328 in salary and former 
controller steven b smotrich 124583 in salary 
heres a man who has no money and the government wants him to 
forfeit millions and millions of dollars said regans attorney 
theodore wells i submit to you that is cruel and unusual 
punishment 
but hansen told the jury that the racketeering statute permitted 
the forfeiture of all interest from an illegal enterprise 
as they chased the almighty dollar they crossed far past the 
line of law hansen said you must decide whether the 
defendants should be stripped of some of their tainted wealth 
the case involved a series of prearranged stock transactions 
from 1984 to 1986 the government alleged during the fiveweek 
trial that the defendants illegally bought and sold stocks to 
generate phony tax losses 
princetonnewport went out of business after the indictment was 
brought last august defense lawyers said at the time that the 
charges alone though unproven destroyed the securities firms 
ability to do business 
besides forfeiture the defendants face up to 20 years in prison 
on each of the two racketeering counts jail terms ranging from 
five to three years for the other charges and fines a sentencing 
date has not been scheduled 
before the lawyers presented their arguments to the jury us 
district judge robert carter ruled that the prosecution could not 
tell the jury about a 650 million fine drexel paid to settle 
securities law charges in another case which also stemmed from the 
boesky scandal 
defense attorneys had argued that telling jurors about the fine 
would prejudice them on the forfeiture question 
