<TEXT>
badly divided house democrats took their fight 
over a capitalgains tax cut behind closed doors today and 
apparently agreed only that opposition should not be a litmus test 
of party loyalty 
speaker thomas s foley dwash said the caucus indicated to 
him that most democrats oppose a major cut in capitalgains tax 
rates as is favored by president bush and a majority of the house 
ways and means committee 
i believe that is bad tax policy bad fiscal policy unwise 
inequitable and illtimed foley said but he added there has 
been no talk of retaliating against democrats who side with bush on 
the issue 
we dont have a guillotine around here foley said 
rep ed jenkins dga a ways and means member who is chief 
sponsor of the proposed rate cut said he has enough votes in 
committee and in the house to pass the plan cutting the tax on 
profits realized from investments in securities or property 
rep dan rostenkowski dill chairman of the committee said 
i think theres a hopeful atmosphere of some kind of 
compromise perhaps along lines of a new plan that he outlined 
tuesday 
his proposal would protect investors from having to pay taxes on 
gains caused by inflation but he declined to provide other 
details he has said he could not support a reduction in the 
capitalgains tax rate 
rostenkowski said he planned to present the idea later today to 
the 13 republican members of his committee who have joined six 
democrats to produce a majority in favor of a rate cut 
a republican committee member who spoke on condition that he 
not be identified by name said there was no chance rostenkowski 
can persuade republicans to drop their support of a rate cut an 
idea already rejected by the white house 
however the first task facing rostenkowski is to win back at 
least one of the six democrats if he does that hell have an 
1818 tie in the committee and wont have to face the caucus in 
the somewhat embarrassing position of being in a minority on his 
own committee 
one of the six democrats rep beryl anthony of arkansas called 
the proposal creative and said it probably could have drawn 
wide support if it had been presented earlier 
its a pretty sound concept but six of us are still committed 
to mr jenkins proposal anthony said 
anthony referred to another of the six rep ed jenkins dga 
chief sponsor of a plan to cut the top capital gains tax rate to 
196 percent for two years and then raise it to 28 percent and 
exclude gains caused by inflation 
the top rate is identical with the top federal income tax rate 
on other income 28 percent or for certain upperincome 
taxpayers 33 percent 
bush has not formally endorsed jenkins plan but administration 
officials have said there was a lot in it they could support 
bushs proposal would set a top rate of 15 percent but it would 
not apply to timber or commercial buildings 
anthony said rostenkowskis plan would exempt gains caused by 
inflation from taxation but neither he nor rostenkowski would give 
further details 
the change would apply to profits from assets sold after dec 
31 1989 
capital gains are increased values of any asset stocks homes 
farms stamp collections or almost anything that has value 
all parties agree that a lower capital gains tax rate increases 
government revenue in the first year or so it is in effect as 
investors take advantage of the rate reduction to get rid of 
investments they no longer find of top appeal 
the democratic leadership of the house including rostenkowski 
has opposed a rate reduction on the grounds that most of the 
benefits would go to taxpayers making more than 100000 a year 
supporters have argued that denial of rate cuts on those grounds is 
nonsensical because it hurts the economy and stifles jobcreating 
new investments 
