<TEXT>
the washington public power supply system 
announced plans wednesday to reenter the financial markets for the 
first time since defaulting on 225 billion in bonds for two 
nuclear plants in 1983 
wppss said it plans to sell 450 million in revenue bonds to 
refund higher interest bonds sold in 1981 and 1982 pricing and 
sale of the bonds for wppss nuclear plants 1 and 3 are expected to 
take place the week of aug 21 
the 1983 default on bonds for nuclear plants 4 and 5 was the 
largest in municipal bond market history wppss bond ratings were 
suspended in 1983 but standard amp poors corp restablished its 
rating late last year 
the refunding bonds are secured by net billing agreements that 
require the bonneville power administration a selffinanced 
federal agency that markets electric power to pay all costs 
connected with projects 1 and 3 
the net billed bonds are the first step in a longawaited 
refunding program to reduce debt service on about 2 billion of 
high interest bonds the supply system also expects to refund 
aproximately 800 million of highinterest bonds issued for project 
2 over the next several years 
at current interest rates the program will reduce the supply 
systems costs an average of 7080 million a year over the next 
30 years don mazur supply system managing director and jim 
jura bonneville administrator said in a statement 
following the wppss default an amendment to federal bankruptcy 
laws clarified that a bankruptcy would not impair protection of 
revenues funds and other assets of projects 1 2 and 3 from claims 
by projects 4 and 5 bondholders 
in contrast to projects 4 and 5 bonds for projects 1 through 3 
are secured by net billing agreements with bonneville which 
markets power from 30 federal hydroelectric projects most in the 
columbia river basin 
wppss is a consortium of utilities that was formed in the early 
1970s to build the five nuclear plants 
bonneville and participating utilities without interruption have 
provided funds for all obligations with respect to supply system 
bonds on projects 1 through 3 since the first bonds were issued in 
1971 
project 2 has been in commercial operation since 1984 projects 
1 and 3 are in extended construction delay because the energy they 
would produce isnt needed presently 
</TEXT>
