<TEXT>
negotiators for boeing co and the 
machinists union began talks wednesday on how much money will go 
into the next union contract and how it will be distributed 
ron eldridge business representative of the machinists 
district 70 in wichita wouldnt reveal the contents of the initial 
proposal the union made to the aerospace company he called it 
fair reasonable and justified 
the machinists current 3year pact with boeing expires oct 3 
industry analysts say the union is in a good position to extract 
favorable terms from boeing a strike is unlikely they say 
primarily because boeing is already having difficulty delivering 
airplanes on time 
the unions have a heck of a lever this time around 
particularly after being given the wire brush the last two times 
around said paul nisbet an aerospace analyst for 
prudentialbache securities inc 
boeing officials declined comment on any aspect of the 
negotiations we do not discuss any of that in the press said 
boeing spokesman paul binder 
eldridge said getting a general wage increase is the top 
priority of the union the machinists at boeing have not had a 
general wage increase for six years with the union settling in 
each of the last two contracts for lumpsum bonuses 
boeing analysts say is likely to again offer substantial 
bonuses in an attempt to avoid a general wage increase that would 
also raise the costs of overtime and benefits and lock the company 
into higher expenses even if economic conditions should turn sour 
what boeing would like to do is give the employees a part of 
the boom times but not get stuck when the weak times come said 
analyst william whitlow of dain bosworth in seattle where boeing 
is based 
the expiring contract paid workers a 12 percent bonus in 1986 
and 5 percent the following two years 
eldridge said surveys of union members showed that as many as 65 
percent of them support the goal of a general wage increase and 
that such sentiment was even stronger in wichita 
since the last contract was negotiated three years ago boeing 
has been amassing record sales and profits on the strength of 
unprecedented orders for new airliners 
just last week boeing announced its earnings for the first six 
months of 1989 were 356 million a 20 percent increase over a year 
earlier the company has nearly 37 billion in cash and 
investments and an order backlog valued at nearly 68 billion 
boeing has until aug 9 to make a counterproposal 
eldridge said he expects the negotiations to be tough boeing 
has a long history of taking you right down to the wire and well 
probably be meeting on oct 3 he said 
</TEXT>
